```

You can also add custom Gradle tasks for different test configurations:

```groovy
// In build.gradle
tasks.register('chromeTests', Test) {
    systemProperty 'browser', 'chrome'
    useJUnitPlatform {
        includeTags 'chrome'
    }
}

tasks.register('firefoxTests', Test) {
    systemProperty 'browser', 'firefox'
    useJUnitPlatform {
        includeTags 'firefox'
    }
}
```

Then you can use these properties in your test setup:

```java
@BeforeEach
public void setUp() throws Exception {
    String browser = System.getProperty("browser", "chrome");
    driver = browser.equals("chrome") ? createChromeDriver() : createFirefoxDriver();
    driver.manage().timeouts().implicitlyWait(Duration.ofSeconds(10));
    driver.manage().window().maximize();
}
```

To run specific browser tests:
```bash
./gradlew chromeTests
./gradlew firefoxTests
```

This setup provides:
- Gradle-based test execution
- Parallel test execution
- Multiple browser support
- Easy configuration through Gradle properties
- Selenium Grid integration with Docker

